article.description:
Becky Hammon scored a season-high 28 points and
Elena Baranova added 23 -- including seven in overtime -- to lead the New York Liberty to a 77-71 victory over the Indiana Fever on Thursday night.
article.headline: Hammon, Baranova help Liberty win in OT
article.linkText: Hammon's 28 points help Liberty top Fever in OT
article.story:
NEW YORK (AP) -- The New York Liberty knew they were in a
must-win situation against the Indiana Fever with the tight Eastern
Conference race winding down.

Becky Hammon scored a season-high 28 points and Elena Baranova
added 23 -- including seven in overtime -- to lead the Liberty to a
77-71 victory over the Fever on Thursday night at Radio City Music
Hall.

"It was a big game for us," Hammon said. "Effort-wise and
intensity-wise, we had to crank it up a level tonight and we did
that. This race is too close. We can't afford to slip up."

Hammon shot 8-for-13 from the field, including 4-for-6 on
3-pointers to help the Liberty (16-16) pull into a tie with
Charlotte and Washington for second place in the East, one game
behind Connecticut.

"There was so much pressure, regardless of us being home or
not," Liberty interim coach Pat Coyle said. "It feels good to
win, but our work isn't done."

Natalie Williams had 18 points and eight rebounds, and Tamika
Catchings and Kelly Miller scored 14 points apiece for the
last-place Fever (15-18), who dropped 1½ games behind the
second-place teams.

Deanna Jackson had 13 points and Miller also had a game-high
seven assists for Indiana, which lost its third straight despite
shooting 47 percent (27-for-57).

After Williams gave Indiana a 60-58 lead with a pair of free
throws with 47.8 seconds left in regulation, Bethany Donaphin sent
the game into overtime with a putback 19 seconds later.

Donaphin, who finished with 11 points, put New York ahead for
good with a jumper 13 seconds into the extra period.

"Bethany did a good job of staying down low and making her
moves," Hammon said. "She played a great game."

Hammon and Baranova also hit jumpers as the Liberty scored the
first six points of overtime.

The Liberty led by as many as seven points twice in overtime,
before Catchings hit a pair of free throws with 16.2 seconds left
to cut Indiana's deficit to 74-71.

Hammon made 1 of 2 free throws with 15.7 seconds remaining, and
Baranova hit two nine seconds later to seal the win.

"We came out and played hard," Catchings said. "We just
weren't able to hit a lot of shots."

Baranova also hit four 3-pointers for New York, which finished
8-for-17 from beyond the arc.

"It was a hard fought, up-and-down game," Indiana coach Brian
Winters said. "The difference was 3-point shots."

The Liberty finished 5-1 at the famed music hall, and will visit
Connecticut on Friday before returning to Madison Square Garden for
the regular-season finale against Washington on Sunday.

"We have a big game against Connecticut," Hammon said. "We
don't want to focus on other people. If we just take care of
ourselves and win our games, everything else should fall into
place."

Indiana ends the season at Connecticut on Sunday.

After New York scored eight straight points to take a 39-31 lead
three minutes into the second half, Indiana went on an 18-4 run
over the next 5½ minutes for a six-point advantage.

The Liberty led 31-29 at halftime, closing the opening period
with a 10-2 run over the final 3:37. Hammon scored eight of her 11
first-half points during that stretch.
